t1XlpubbdBgeWbs2akOpD_33BlrM3L1Cp7Unqa3_HwM6tWytLvOL8DKoCzmuU3x1XWbUEA4k9Y9=
An09s38P177-KMkcKt2ZgGUQAqFSJmnR_CPTaqFRVuW5P1ZUz4-u-1nHXw31klYJaAz_9fTEThk=
EZHHKcwIzu7VlgjgsdWhTgLEqI6HIK5XKuzUYIWg2dX49kQZhuhwbQ7h3QQkg7I6UII_4OU9T4m=
9ls7w3WLSJ6A6GnuC4LWdH7f_VdaBA6eu4ESUqbslczaW0DlCBWO-Eh7D9_X4p5Et_EvrOz4_X8=
WLHgiiaYKxWmrR-N1A4tOmMWdajdzzqOv2w8CyA ) :

To return to Shopify, if the company believes that their main quest is buil=
ding out storefronts and incorporating AI and whatever else, and that thing=
s like logistics are side quests best handled by focused partners, then it=
=E2=80=99s pretty hard to justify not supporting Buy with Prime for any rea=
son other than bare-knuckled self interest =E2=80=94 and from my perspectiv=
e that=E2=80=99s understandable! That story, though, is a much harder sell =
for Shopify=E2=80=99s merchants, who could previously be mollified by the f=
act that Shopify was spending serious money on building out their own logis=
tics alternative=E2=80=A6

Indeed, maybe that gets at where there is a potential for an agreement betw=
een Shopify and Amazon: from Amazon=E2=80=99s perspective the data from bei=
ng the payment provider would certainly be nice to have, particularly if it=
 can be tied back into the consumer-facing business; if Amazon really is me=
aningfully shifting beyond Aggregation, though, then there is value in havi=
ng Shopify merchants using its logistics even without payments. And, just l=
ike before, Shopify could sweeten the deal, perhaps by cutting Amazon in on=
 some of its payment margins (slight though they may be).

This would be a win for both sides: Shopify=E2=80=99s merchants could use B=
uy with Prime, Amazon could get the extra volume (and merchant fees) and a =
bit of margin (and besides, ATT makes third-party data less valuable anyway=
s), and Shopify could well and truly focus on its main quest without having=
 to find out whether the logistics side quest was in fact an essential defe=
nse against an opponent that could upend the board completely.

Everyone wins: Amazon, merchants, and Shopify (or, at a minimum, Shopify do=
esn=E2=80=99t lose).

The Payments Question
---------------------

This points to what is the biggest question about this deal: how exactly ar=
e payments being handled? This is how Amazon characterized the relationship=
 in its press release ( https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/202308301159=
54/en/ ) :

The Buy with Prime app for Shopify gives Prime members the option to select=
 Buy with Prime on a product=E2=80=99s detail page before completing their =
order within Shopify=E2=80=99s Checkout. Buy with Prime offers Prime member=
s fast, free delivery and easy returns through Amazon=E2=80=99s fulfillment=
 network. After signing into their Amazon accounts, Prime members pay for t=
heir orders using a payment method from their Amazon wallets and Shopify Pa=
yments will process the payment through Shopify=E2=80=99s Checkout.

I haven=E2=80=99t seen any live Shopify pages with Buy With Prime , but Ama=
zon=E2=80=99s web page ( https://buywithprime.amazon.com/shopify ) had some=
 illustrations:

Amazon's illustration of the Buy with Prime flow ( https://buywithprime.ama=
zon.com/shopify )

First, you obviously can only Buy with Prime goods that are a part of Prime=
; that is why a Shopify cart can=E2=80=99t mix Prime and non-Prime goods. T=
o put it another way, you decide on your wallet and logistics provider when=
 you select the good, not when you check out.

Secondly, while Shopify is indeed processing the payments, keep in mind tha=
t everything else is using Amazon logistics: you as a seller are paying Ama=
zon to hold inventory, you=E2=80=99re being charged a fulfillment fee and a=
 Prime order fee. That means that Amazon has a means to charge you for a re=
turn, as well, and from a user perspective they can also send the money to =
the correct credit card because it was selected in their wallet. As for the=
 processing fees captured by Shopify, well, those usually aren=E2=80=99t re=
turned to the merchant anyways.

The remaining question, then, is if Shopify is indeed sharing some of its p=
ayment processing profits with Amazon; the previous two sections made Amazo=
n feel inevitable, and Shopify desperate, but this Business Insider article=
 says its the opposite ( https://www.businessinsider.com/inside-clash-betwe=
en-amazon-shopify-over-buy-with-prime-2023-9 ) :

The internet giant has been trying to get its Buy with Prime service on Sho=
pify=E2=80=99s merchant platform for months. It finally happened on Wednesd=
ay. But the untold story of how it happened reveals that Shopify exerted a =
surprising amount of leverage over the negotiations.

One of the most interesting parts of the story is how important it was to A=
mazon to ensure Buy with Prime metrics appeared within the Shopify dashboar=
d, for fear that merchants wouldn=E2=80=99t want to deal with multiple sour=
ces of information; another is that Amazon apparently built the vast majori=
ty of the integration, with minimal contribution from Shopify.

The bigger takeaway, though, is that Amazon seemed to want this integration=
 much more than Shopify, and if I=E2=80=99m right about Buy with Prime bein=
g a major strategic initiative from the very top of the company than that m=
akes sense. Also remember that Shopify=E2=80=99s biggest motivation to agre=
e with this deal is to mollify merchants; they certainly seem to have dragg=
ed their feet. To that end, it may be that Shopify isn=E2=80=99t sharing an=
y payment margin at all, particularly given that Amazon likely has returns,=
 its biggest reason to control payments, covered.

That would certainly be a big victory for Shopify in this specific battle, =
but it is of course part of a broader victory for Amazon in the e-commerce =
war. With this deal Amazon has just dramatically increased the total addres=
sable market for its logistics service, just as AWS long ago dramatically i=
ncreased the total addressable market for Amazon=E2=80=99s back-end infrast=
ructure, once again giving Amazon even better leverage on its unmatched wil=
lingness to invest.

